com.reactivecascade.util

Class DoubleQueue<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • java.util.concurrent.LinkedBlockingQueue<T>
          • com.reactivecascade.util.DoubleQueue<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - queue item type
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<T>, Collection<T>, BlockingQueue<T>, Queue<T>

    public class DoubleQueue<T>
extends LinkedBlockingQueue<T>
    A LinkedBlockingQueue which, if empty, pulls information from a second lower absolute priority BlockingQueue.

    This is designed for allowing one of the Async.WORKER threads to operate as an in-order single threaded executor which reverts to help with the common AsyncBuilder.getWorkerQueue() tasks when no in-order tasks are pending.

    Note clearly there is an upside and downside to this design vs making your own IThreadType. The upside is performance and lower peak memory usage. We have fewer threads contending for background work so less resources and less and faster context switches (context switches tend to cost marginally more as thread count increases). The downside is delays fom other background tasks unrelated to this may slow the start of execution. A very slow task pulled from the Async.WORKER queue and perhaps unrelated to the current focus of your attention will, once started, block the next DoubleQueue item from starting until it completes.

    In practice this performs well for most uses since everything is best effort anyway and the single thread has absolute priority. If starting as soon as possible is absolutely critical, use a dedicated IThreadType instead.

      • take

        @CallSuper
 @NonNull
public T take()
                            throws InterruptedException
        Poll both queues for work to do. This will wake up immediately if new work is added to this queue, and within the next polling time window for the lowPriorityQueue. Since other threads which may be taking work from the low priority queue are probably waking up immediately this is OK. It keeps any dual-use thread associated with this queue relatively free for immediate response to the single use queue until such time as all other threads are busy, subscribe it pitches in on the work any of them can do.
        Specified by:
        take in interface BlockingQueue<T>
        Overrides:
        take in class LinkedBlockingQueue<T>
        Returns:
        the value from the high priority queue, or (if high priority is empty) the low priority queue
        Throws:
        InterruptedException - interrupt event
